WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.940 --> 00:00:06.004
Professor Donald
Kagan: We have been looking

00:00:06.004 --> 00:00:10.670
at the question of the rise of
the polis and the various

00:00:10.670 --> 00:00:14.810
significant elements that were
part of the making of the

00:00:14.810 --> 00:00:20.021
polis,
and of course I've emphasized

00:00:20.021 --> 00:00:27.455
the notion of this new class of
people, the farmer hoplite

00:00:27.455 --> 00:00:30.791
citizen,
as being the critical element

00:00:30.791 --> 00:00:34.659
in shaping the polis and
for my money that's what the

00:00:34.659 --> 00:00:38.266
polis is about to start
with and then it develops

00:00:38.266 --> 00:00:41.020
characteristics consistent with
that,

00:00:41.020 --> 00:00:44.560
and some that challenge that
over the centuries.

00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:49.253
But now, imagine that we are
living in the early years of a

00:00:49.253 --> 00:00:53.300
polis sometime in the
eighth century B.C.

00:00:53.300 --> 00:00:56.218
Again, I want to emphasize
these things that I've been

00:00:56.218 --> 00:00:59.686
describing don't happen in every
place at the same time and they

00:00:59.686 --> 00:01:02.439
don't even happen every place in
the same way,

00:01:02.439 --> 00:01:06.826
but over a stretch of time the
concepts and the kind of

00:01:06.826 --> 00:01:11.376
characteristics I've been
describing appear to spread all

00:01:11.376 --> 00:01:15.755
over the place.
But one of the ways in which we

00:01:15.755 --> 00:01:21.062
can date the time when the
polis came into being has

00:01:21.062 --> 00:01:26.276
to do with the Greek traditions
about the establishment of

00:01:26.276 --> 00:01:30.759
colonies throughout the
Mediterranean inhabited by

00:01:30.759 --> 00:01:34.454
Greeks,
and the reason that they are a

00:01:34.454 --> 00:01:37.833
clue is because every time we
see a colony,

00:01:37.833 --> 00:01:43.041
learn anything at all about it,
it appears to exist in the form

00:01:43.041 --> 00:01:46.867
of a polis,
which powerfully suggests that

00:01:46.867 --> 00:01:50.693
that was the typical
characteristic style of life

00:01:50.693 --> 00:01:54.679
that had already been
established for Greeks before

00:01:54.679 --> 00:02:00.155
they sent out the colonies.
So, that's the chronological

00:02:00.155 --> 00:02:05.473
significance of it.
I should say all of these

00:02:05.473 --> 00:02:12.390
dates that I will be giving you
are some combination of Greek

00:02:12.390 --> 00:02:18.154
tradition--and the Greeks dated
these colonies very

00:02:18.154 --> 00:02:22.439
specifically.
That would be hard to believe,

00:02:22.439 --> 00:02:26.047
impossible to believe,
I guess, if it weren't that

00:02:26.047 --> 00:02:29.949
these dates tend to be confirmed
in a general way,

00:02:29.949 --> 00:02:33.586
not in a specific way,
by the archaeological

00:02:33.586 --> 00:02:36.970
discoveries that we find at the
sites,

00:02:36.970 --> 00:02:40.900
the earliest places where these
colonies came into being.

00:02:40.900 --> 00:02:44.073
So it's that combination,
archaeology plus Greek

00:02:44.073 --> 00:02:47.449
tradition that lies behind the
date of any city.

00:02:47.449 --> 00:02:50.961
But you shouldn't take the date
that I give you,

00:02:50.961 --> 00:02:53.800
the traditional date,
as being firm.

00:02:53.800 --> 00:02:56.893
It's a general thing;
it's around that time is the

00:02:56.893 --> 00:03:00.599
best we can really say.
The date that's sort of typical

00:03:00.599 --> 00:03:04.385
for the general phenomenon of
colonization coming out of the

00:03:04.385 --> 00:03:08.750
mother cities of Greece is again
that date we keep talking about,

00:03:08.750 --> 00:03:11.916
750 roughly.
But in fact,

00:03:11.916 --> 00:03:16.581
the earliest date according to
Greek tradition,

00:03:16.581 --> 00:03:21.387
if my memory is correct,
was something like 773 where

00:03:21.387 --> 00:03:25.671
the Greeks date the foundation
of what they thought was the

00:03:25.671 --> 00:03:29.881
earliest colony they ever
established -- a place that they

00:03:29.881 --> 00:03:34.707
called Pithaecusa,
which is the island of Ischia

00:03:34.707 --> 00:03:38.824
in the Bay of Naples.
That's the very first place

00:03:38.824 --> 00:03:42.379
where there is a tradition of a
Greek colony having been

00:03:42.379 --> 00:03:45.603
planted.
There's no question that there

00:03:45.603 --> 00:03:50.882
was a Greek colony there and as
I say the archaeological remains

00:03:50.882 --> 00:03:54.819
confirm the general time for
this happening.

00:03:54.819 --> 00:03:59.278
Now, the first question I
suppose, before I get to

00:03:59.278 --> 00:04:03.400
describing what a colony was and
how it worked,

00:04:03.400 --> 00:04:09.091
we want to ask the question
what was it that led Greeks to

00:04:09.091 --> 00:04:12.885
sail or walk,
mostly to sail very great

00:04:12.885 --> 00:04:16.779
distances from their mother
cities.

00:04:16.779 --> 00:04:22.611
To leave home and to establish
a new city for themselves

00:04:22.611 --> 00:04:27.699
someplace else is not to be
taken for granted.

00:04:27.699 --> 00:04:31.244
In the first place,
by and until the twentieth

00:04:31.244 --> 00:04:34.709
century, I guess,
human beings tended to stay

00:04:34.709 --> 00:04:36.887
put.
They didn't move,

00:04:36.887 --> 00:04:39.889
unless they were driven to
move.

00:04:39.889 --> 00:04:43.371
That was the natural thing to
do given the character of life,

00:04:43.371 --> 00:04:46.973
which was based upon farming,
if you leave you lose your

00:04:46.973 --> 00:04:50.790
farm, and based upon the
difficulty of transportation.

00:04:50.790 --> 00:04:53.867
In the Greek world we know--I
think I quoted something from

00:04:53.867 --> 00:04:56.240
Hesiod that confirmed it.
The Greeks were,

00:04:56.240 --> 00:04:59.649
even though they went to sea
plenty, they were terrified of

00:04:59.649 --> 00:05:02.306
the sea for very good reason.
Their ships,

00:05:02.306 --> 00:05:04.699
their boats were not very
seaworthy;

00:05:04.699 --> 00:05:08.199
storms come up in the
Mediterranean very suddenly and

00:05:08.199 --> 00:05:10.128
terribly;
you take your life in your

00:05:10.128 --> 00:05:12.583
hands when you travel.
So then there's the whole

00:05:12.583 --> 00:05:15.952
idea--we've already given you
some sense that the Greeks were

00:05:15.952 --> 00:05:19.279
ancestor worshippers.
I mean, they took special care

00:05:19.279 --> 00:05:23.105
of the dead and they thought
that the way you buried people

00:05:23.105 --> 00:05:25.480
and so on was terribly
important.

00:05:25.480 --> 00:05:29.107
So, what I'm saying is,
when you leave the place you

00:05:29.107 --> 00:05:32.379
were born, you leave your
ancestors as well.

00:05:32.379 --> 00:05:37.421
All of that means we need to
explain why these folks do what

00:05:37.421 --> 00:05:41.171
they end up doing,
and we have some hints,

00:05:41.171 --> 00:05:45.877
but of course we do not know
with any certainty or any

00:05:45.877 --> 00:05:49.824
confidence.
If you ask the question why

00:05:49.824 --> 00:05:55.145
did many Italians leave their
homes, especially south Italians

00:05:55.145 --> 00:05:59.420
in the late nineteenth century
and come--well,

00:05:59.420 --> 00:06:01.983
go all over the world actually,
to South America,

00:06:01.983 --> 00:06:05.080
Australia, but the largest
numbers to the United States.

00:06:05.080 --> 00:06:07.750
Why did they do that?
Well, we don't have to do a lot

00:06:07.750 --> 00:06:11.136
of guessing.
We have written evidence from

00:06:11.136 --> 00:06:15.939
the people who went and they say
why they did it.

00:06:15.939 --> 00:06:18.206
We can then supplement that
with all sorts of other

00:06:18.206 --> 00:06:21.456
information that we have,
but we don't have any documents

00:06:21.456 --> 00:06:25.509
from some settler explaining why
he's going where he's going.

00:06:25.509 --> 00:06:30.500
So, we have to reason from the
evidence that the establishment

00:06:30.500 --> 00:06:35.550
gives us.
I suppose the most widely cited

00:06:35.550 --> 00:06:42.110
reason is simply the desire to
acquire farmland.

00:06:42.110 --> 00:06:45.540
Remember, I keep emphasizing
this.

00:06:45.540 --> 00:06:51.462
The vast overwhelming majority
of people needed to farm land,

00:06:51.462 --> 00:06:55.935
in order to stay alive.
And why should there be a

00:06:55.935 --> 00:06:58.637
shortage of farmland?
One answer,

00:06:58.637 --> 00:07:02.139
and it's the one that is most
widely believed among Greek

00:07:02.139 --> 00:07:04.452
scholars,
is that the growth of

00:07:04.452 --> 00:07:08.544
population that we have
mentioned in connection with the

00:07:08.544 --> 00:07:12.190
rise of the polis is
still working once the

00:07:12.190 --> 00:07:16.761
polis comes into form.
So what this means,

00:07:16.761 --> 00:07:22.562
if you used to have two
children and now you have four,

00:07:22.562 --> 00:07:26.860
how do you provide for the
extra two?

00:07:26.860 --> 00:07:29.701
Well, sometimes you divide up
the land equally,

00:07:29.701 --> 00:07:33.160
but if that land continues to
get smaller and smaller,

00:07:33.160 --> 00:07:35.837
it will not sustain an
additional person,

00:07:35.837 --> 00:07:38.180
not to mention additional
family.

00:07:38.180 --> 00:07:41.858
If you were to follow the
procedure, which the Greeks did

00:07:41.858 --> 00:07:45.166
not, of primogenitor,
that is, of giving the whole

00:07:45.166 --> 00:07:48.759
plot to the eldest son,
but what happens to the others?

00:07:48.759 --> 00:07:55.170
So that clearly is a problem
and the notion that land hunger

00:07:55.170 --> 00:07:59.574
is a key explanation,
I think, is supported by the

00:07:59.574 --> 00:08:02.362
fact that wherever we find a
polis,

00:08:02.362 --> 00:08:05.149
whatever other characteristics
it has,

00:08:05.149 --> 00:08:09.071
and they vary,
some of them are located at

00:08:09.071 --> 00:08:13.949
wonderful places on the sea for
trading purposes,

00:08:13.949 --> 00:08:19.114
some of them are not,
but all of them have a land

00:08:19.114 --> 00:08:24.817
supply which permits the
citizens to farm successfully

00:08:24.817 --> 00:08:30.089
and thereby to make the
polis succeed.

00:08:30.089 --> 00:08:34.139
But I don't think that's
the only answer.

00:08:34.139 --> 00:08:38.609
I think the desire for commerce
would have been also--I agree

00:08:38.609 --> 00:08:43.228
with the traditional view which
is that this would have been at

00:08:43.228 --> 00:08:47.539
a lesser consideration,
but still very important,

00:08:47.539 --> 00:08:53.059
because we so often find that
the colony is placed right at a

00:08:53.059 --> 00:08:57.556
nifty place for trade.
They would have had to be damn

00:08:57.556 --> 00:09:01.510
fools to have settled there
without that being in their

00:09:01.510 --> 00:09:03.870
minds,
although some of the places

00:09:03.870 --> 00:09:07.210
where they settled leave us
puzzled, and have left the

00:09:07.210 --> 00:09:11.764
ancients puzzled.
One of my favorite examples is

00:09:11.764 --> 00:09:16.705
the colony on the south shore of
the Bosporus,

00:09:16.705 --> 00:09:19.890
which is called Chalcedon.

00:09:23.059 --> 00:09:26.928
It's right opposite
Constantinople--that doesn't

00:09:26.928 --> 00:09:29.602
exist, Istanbul.
Winston Churchill never,

00:09:29.602 --> 00:09:31.440
never conceded that it was
Istanbul;

00:09:31.440 --> 00:09:35.110
he called it Constantinople
till the day he died.

00:09:35.110 --> 00:09:39.062
But right opposite that
magnificent site,

00:09:39.062 --> 00:09:43.753
the golden horn is there.
How could you possibly settle

00:09:43.753 --> 00:09:47.240
there, because they settled
Chalcedon first and the

00:09:47.240 --> 00:09:51.217
tradition that the Greeks pass
on is the people who settle

00:09:51.217 --> 00:09:55.234
Chalcedon were blind men,
because you would have to be

00:09:55.234 --> 00:09:59.520
blind to make that choice.
Well, we don't know why they

00:09:59.520 --> 00:10:02.580
did what they did.
So nonetheless,

00:10:02.580 --> 00:10:06.216
the desire for a good
commercial opportunity might

00:10:06.216 --> 00:10:10.298
well have been one of the
elements that these people who

00:10:10.298 --> 00:10:13.490
were leaving their home cities
sought.

00:10:13.490 --> 00:10:19.129
Then there are less--what's the
word I want?

00:10:19.129 --> 00:10:22.913
Certainly things that have
nothing to do with economics

00:10:22.913 --> 00:10:27.047
really--there are politics going
on in these states as there

00:10:27.047 --> 00:10:29.919
always are in any Greek
polis.

00:10:29.919 --> 00:10:33.101
There are factions that grow up
for one reason or another and

00:10:33.101 --> 00:10:36.701
they come into conflict.
One side wins the argument and

00:10:36.701 --> 00:10:40.995
the battle, and sometimes the
ill will is so great that the

00:10:40.995 --> 00:10:45.659
losing side feels either that it
has to flee for its safety,

00:10:45.659 --> 00:10:49.527
or it chooses to flee rather
than to live under their

00:10:49.527 --> 00:10:52.640
opponents.
So, defeated political groups

00:10:52.640 --> 00:10:57.234
might well--or individuals who
were the heads of those groups

00:10:57.234 --> 00:11:00.679
might decide they have to get
out of town.

00:11:00.679 --> 00:11:03.669
And now that we do have
something, namely,

00:11:03.669 --> 00:11:07.460
this wave of colonization,
they join that as well.

00:11:07.460 --> 00:11:11.500
Then there are always
things that we might call much

00:11:11.500 --> 00:11:16.123
less rational than that.
In any group of people there is

00:11:16.123 --> 00:11:19.888
a small minority,
I want to emphasize small,

00:11:19.888 --> 00:11:23.040
who just love to do risky
things.

00:11:23.040 --> 00:11:27.305
They just love adventure;
they're never happy if they're

00:11:27.305 --> 00:11:32.042
safe, and so off they go seeking
adventure and seeking to make a

00:11:32.042 --> 00:11:35.200
fortune however they're going to
do it,

00:11:35.200 --> 00:11:38.612
so I think that has to be
counted into the picture too,

00:11:38.612 --> 00:11:42.468
so typically I think it would
have been a small part of what's

00:11:42.468 --> 00:11:45.152
going on.
So, for these reasons and

00:11:45.152 --> 00:11:49.100
probably for hundred more that I
haven't thought of,

00:11:49.100 --> 00:11:53.841
we can understand why these
people go against the natural

00:11:53.841 --> 00:11:57.990
instinct of staying put and go
adventuring out,

00:11:57.990 --> 00:12:02.580
seeking a new home someplace in
the Mediterranean.

00:12:02.580 --> 00:12:06.549
Okay, what are these new
settlements like?

00:12:06.549 --> 00:12:09.949
First thing is that they're
like each other in many

00:12:09.949 --> 00:12:12.532
important ways,
although obviously with

00:12:12.532 --> 00:12:16.781
differences from place to place.
But here's how it worked--by

00:12:16.781 --> 00:12:20.448
the way, the word I have been
using, colony is not a Greek

00:12:20.448 --> 00:12:24.629
word and really not appropriate
for what the Greeks are up to.

00:12:24.629 --> 00:12:28.579
The Greek word for this is,
apoikia,

00:12:28.579 --> 00:12:32.716
and most literally it would
mean a home away,

00:12:32.716 --> 00:12:37.230
an away home and that's what
they're making.

00:12:37.230 --> 00:12:39.896
They are establishing for
themselves a household,

00:12:39.896 --> 00:12:42.396
a home someplace away from
where they started,

00:12:42.396 --> 00:12:45.614
and that's the name.
Colony is a Latin word

00:12:45.614 --> 00:12:50.669
ultimately for colonia
and the Roman colonies were,

00:12:50.669 --> 00:12:54.064
first of all,
garrisons that they planted in

00:12:54.064 --> 00:12:58.090
land they had conquered to keep
the people quiet.

00:12:58.090 --> 00:13:05.049
So, they would be alien bosses
in a different territory.

00:13:05.049 --> 00:13:08.252
And then later in history,
in Roman history,

00:13:08.252 --> 00:13:11.529
that was the name given to
establishments,

00:13:11.529 --> 00:13:16.983
rural establishments,
when the civilization was

00:13:16.983 --> 00:13:23.741
breaking down and the men who
worked on those rural places

00:13:23.741 --> 00:13:29.151
really were not free men.
They were the antecedents of

00:13:29.151 --> 00:13:33.305
the Serfs, which we will see
later on in medieval history in

00:13:33.305 --> 00:13:35.444
Europe.
So, when you see the word

00:13:35.444 --> 00:13:38.598
colonia in late Roman
history, it's talking about

00:13:38.598 --> 00:13:41.180
something very,
very different from what we're

00:13:41.180 --> 00:13:44.259
talking about.
So, I use the word colony

00:13:44.259 --> 00:13:49.112
because that's what we have for
all such establishments of the

00:13:49.112 --> 00:13:52.873
kind we're talking about.
Remember that these are

00:13:52.873 --> 00:13:55.940
apoikiai from the Greek
point of view.

00:13:55.940 --> 00:14:01.690
Okay, how does an
apoikia happen?

00:14:01.690 --> 00:14:08.095
Somebody in one of the old
Greek cities has to decide that

00:14:08.095 --> 00:14:13.039
he wants to go out and establish
a colony.

00:14:13.039 --> 00:14:16.792
He would be an individual of
some eminence,

00:14:16.792 --> 00:14:21.796
because the job of doing this
requires that people should

00:14:21.796 --> 00:14:25.694
accept his leadership.
He will have to do the

00:14:25.694 --> 00:14:29.629
recruiting of people that come
with him on the colony;

00:14:29.629 --> 00:14:33.370
he will have to do the
constitutional discussion and a

00:14:33.370 --> 00:14:37.887
political discussion to gain the
sanction from the mother city to

00:14:37.887 --> 00:14:40.710
allow him to do everything he
knows.

00:14:40.710 --> 00:14:45.145
So, I think we should imagine
that these leaders of colonies,

00:14:45.145 --> 00:14:50.433
these founders of colonies,
would be probably noblemen and

00:14:50.433 --> 00:14:55.149
that they would have a position
of eminence,

00:14:55.149 --> 00:15:00.656
and yet unlikely to be part of
the sort of dominant faction in

00:15:00.656 --> 00:15:05.350
that city, because otherwise why
would they leave?

00:15:05.350 --> 00:15:08.419
Anyway, the Greeks had a name
for this individual.

00:15:08.419 --> 00:15:11.720
He was called an
oikistes;

00:15:11.720 --> 00:15:16.581
he is the found of the colony.
So, now he has decided to

00:15:16.581 --> 00:15:19.264
do it and he's gained
recognition from the town

00:15:19.264 --> 00:15:21.890
council, let's say,
and he can go forward.

00:15:25.010 --> 00:15:27.786
Now, he has to have an idea.
He can't just say,

00:15:27.786 --> 00:15:30.399
I think I'd like to found a
colony.

00:15:30.399 --> 00:15:34.976
What is more typical,
I think, is that he thinks,

00:15:34.976 --> 00:15:39.743
I would like to take and have
found a colony on the

00:15:39.743 --> 00:15:44.549
southeastern coast of Sicily.
Why?

00:15:44.549 --> 00:15:46.950
Because he knows something
about it;

00:15:46.950 --> 00:15:51.735
either he has somehow traveled
out there himself and said,

00:15:51.735 --> 00:15:56.269
the place I'm thinking about
has a wonderful harbor,

00:15:56.269 --> 00:15:59.569
it has good farmland in the
neighborhood,

00:15:59.569 --> 00:16:04.188
and a critical element to
making this judgment is that it

00:16:04.188 --> 00:16:08.230
is not occupied by hostile
natives who will resist

00:16:08.230 --> 00:16:12.604
vigorously your landing there.
Either there will be nobody

00:16:12.604 --> 00:16:15.830
there or more likely there will
be not a very big population,

00:16:15.830 --> 00:16:19.317
and it's not very tough,
and they could be easily

00:16:19.317 --> 00:16:22.317
brushed aside.
Those would have been some of

00:16:22.317 --> 00:16:25.486
the considerations,
and so what the oikistes

00:16:25.486 --> 00:16:29.352
does when he has picked out in
his own mind where he wanted to

00:16:29.352 --> 00:16:33.559
go,
next he goes to Delphi.

00:16:33.559 --> 00:16:38.259
Anybody--raise your hand if
you've been to Delphi.

00:16:38.259 --> 00:16:42.718
When you go to Greece do the
obvious, go where the tourists

00:16:42.718 --> 00:16:45.870
go and Delphi is one place not
to miss.

00:16:45.870 --> 00:16:50.676
It's halfway up Mount Parnassus
and it was thought by the Greeks

00:16:50.676 --> 00:16:54.643
to be the omphalos,
the navel of the universe,

00:16:54.643 --> 00:16:57.740
the center in every way.
Why?

00:16:57.740 --> 00:17:04.289
Because there the god Apollo
had established an oracle.

00:17:04.289 --> 00:17:11.455
There was a place in which from
the earth there came--it wasn't

00:17:11.455 --> 00:17:16.413
steam, what would it be?
Gases would escape through this

00:17:16.413 --> 00:17:20.003
gap in the earth and there when
things got figured out and

00:17:20.003 --> 00:17:21.930
arranged,
there were priests who

00:17:21.930 --> 00:17:25.230
worshipped Apollo there and who
took care of this phenomenon.

00:17:25.230 --> 00:17:31.468
They would place a young woman
there who would sit as these

00:17:31.468 --> 00:17:37.170
gases came up and she would
after a while begin to,

00:17:37.170 --> 00:17:40.772
I suppose in the biblical
languages, she would speak in

00:17:40.772 --> 00:17:44.307
tongues, which is to say she
would rattle off a lot of

00:17:44.307 --> 00:17:48.509
language which nobody could
understand what she was saying.

00:17:48.509 --> 00:17:53.855
Gibberish, or so it sounded,
or Greek but making no sense to

00:17:53.855 --> 00:17:59.109
anybody, and then the priest
would listen to this stuff and

00:17:59.109 --> 00:18:03.091
he would say,
what Apollo said through the

00:18:03.091 --> 00:18:07.450
priestess here is,
and he would give the message.

00:18:07.450 --> 00:18:10.299
Let me just take a moment to
tell you about this.

00:18:10.299 --> 00:18:14.459
I say this now with great
confidence but ten years ago

00:18:14.459 --> 00:18:18.069
this story, which all the Greeks
agreed too,

00:18:18.069 --> 00:18:20.863
agreed upon in every respect,
that the temple of Apollo was

00:18:20.863 --> 00:18:24.142
built right on top of this,
and underneath the floor of the

00:18:24.142 --> 00:18:27.359
temple was this little room
where the gases came up,

00:18:27.359 --> 00:18:29.720
where the priestess sat,
where all of this came up.

00:18:29.720 --> 00:18:32.634
Well, archaeologists
investigated this carefully,

00:18:32.634 --> 00:18:35.488
and the French School of
Archaeology late in the

00:18:35.488 --> 00:18:38.767
nineteenth century dug
everything up and concluded this

00:18:38.767 --> 00:18:40.970
was baloney;
it was a myth.

00:18:40.970 --> 00:18:45.402
There were no gases coming up
from any of this stuff,

00:18:45.402 --> 00:18:49.579
and so everybody believed for
the next century,

00:18:49.579 --> 00:18:54.467
and then a young man who once
sat in one of the chairs--not in

00:18:54.467 --> 00:18:58.427
this room maybe,
but in which you're sitting,

00:18:58.427 --> 00:19:02.833
John Hale of the Yale Class of
1973, who is now an

00:19:02.833 --> 00:19:07.240
archaeologist at the University
of Louisville.

00:19:07.240 --> 00:19:09.840
Having learned,
or having agreed,

00:19:09.840 --> 00:19:14.880
let's say, with my prejudice,
that the higher naivetÃ©

00:19:14.880 --> 00:19:17.453
must reign--and if the Greeks
said it happened,

00:19:17.453 --> 00:19:20.865
you got to believe it happened,
until you have to believe that

00:19:20.865 --> 00:19:23.821
it didn't happen.
And so he decided to

00:19:23.821 --> 00:19:28.988
investigate this and he took
with him a fine geologist from

00:19:28.988 --> 00:19:34.154
Wesleyan just to go to the place
there at Delphi and to see

00:19:34.154 --> 00:19:39.410
whether it could be true that
such gases did come out,

00:19:39.410 --> 00:19:43.248
and what sort of gases they
were, and what consequences they

00:19:43.248 --> 00:19:46.761
would have, and you know I
wouldn't be telling you this

00:19:46.761 --> 00:19:50.534
story if it hadn't turned out
that they discovered evidence

00:19:50.534 --> 00:19:52.171
that,
in my judgment,

00:19:52.171 --> 00:19:55.241
but I don't think really
anybody doubts it anymore,

00:19:55.241 --> 00:19:57.819
that totally confirmed the
Greek story.

00:19:57.819 --> 00:20:01.303
They tell you precisely what
the gases were,

00:20:01.303 --> 00:20:05.109
what the characteristics of
those gases were,

00:20:05.109 --> 00:20:10.712
and it squared beautifully with
all details that we heard about

00:20:10.712 --> 00:20:14.971
the Delphic Oracle.
So, here's just one more case

00:20:14.971 --> 00:20:18.799
where Yale helped to straighten
out the world,

00:20:18.799 --> 00:20:22.306
but you notice it wasn't done
by a Yale faculty member,

00:20:22.306 --> 00:20:24.579
we engage in confusing the
world,

00:20:24.579 --> 00:20:29.451
but our alumni do a much better
job and that's what happened

00:20:29.451 --> 00:20:32.755
here.
So, you go to the oracle

00:20:32.755 --> 00:20:37.379
and what do you ask the oracle?
Well now, before we go any

00:20:37.379 --> 00:20:40.339
further--in your Herodotus
readings and elsewhere,

00:20:40.339 --> 00:20:44.182
you will come across many a
story in which an oracle is

00:20:44.182 --> 00:20:48.906
consulted and gives an answer.
Well, the most famous early on,

00:20:48.906 --> 00:20:53.089
King Croesus of Lydia,
the richest man in the world,

00:20:53.089 --> 00:20:55.681
you've heard all about him,
decides it would be a nice

00:20:55.681 --> 00:20:57.540
thing to conquer the Persian
Empire,

00:20:57.540 --> 00:21:00.433
his neighbor to the east.
So, he goes to--he's a

00:21:00.433 --> 00:21:03.633
barbarian, but the barbarians
came to the Delphic Oracle too,

00:21:03.633 --> 00:21:06.140
because you want to know what
the gods want.

00:21:06.140 --> 00:21:10.537
So, he came and he asked.
He said, "If I cross the Halys

00:21:10.537 --> 00:21:15.292
River, that's the boundary
between Lydia and Persia,

00:21:15.292 --> 00:21:18.875
what will happen?"
The oracle replied,

00:21:18.875 --> 00:21:23.323
"A great empire will be
destroyed," and Croesus said,

00:21:23.323 --> 00:21:26.829
"Terrific that's what I have in
mind."

00:21:26.829 --> 00:21:30.729
He invaded and he was
clobbered, and then you read the

00:21:30.729 --> 00:21:34.849
splendid story Herodotus tells
of how he was captured.

00:21:34.849 --> 00:21:38.860
He was up on a pyre,
and he was going to be burned

00:21:38.860 --> 00:21:42.971
when he remembered Solon,
the Greek, who had come to him

00:21:42.971 --> 00:21:46.140
and warned him about the vain
glory, and he said,

00:21:46.140 --> 00:21:49.621
oh Solon, oh Solon.
I guess Apollo must have then

00:21:49.621 --> 00:21:53.880
said, he's reached wisdom and so
he sent a rainstorm to put the

00:21:53.880 --> 00:21:56.490
fire out and he lived through
that.

00:21:56.490 --> 00:22:00.313
Well okay,
the point is the oracle was

00:22:00.313 --> 00:22:02.839
wrong.
No, of course not.

00:22:02.839 --> 00:22:04.869
We all know what was wrong with
Croesus.

00:22:04.869 --> 00:22:08.300
He should have asked another
question, which empire?

00:22:08.300 --> 00:22:12.208
But he didn't think of it;
other times all kinds of funny

00:22:12.208 --> 00:22:16.014
stories are told about the
oracle, which would suggest that

00:22:16.014 --> 00:22:19.819
it wasn't really a very reliable
source of information,

00:22:19.819 --> 00:22:22.278
that it was filled with
mythology and so on and so

00:22:22.278 --> 00:22:24.299
forth.
But here is the hard headed

00:22:24.299 --> 00:22:26.318
fact.
We know for sure Greeks and

00:22:26.318 --> 00:22:30.066
barbarians, and everybody came
to Delphi, and when you came to

00:22:30.066 --> 00:22:33.200
Delphi and you were going to
consult the oracle,

00:22:33.200 --> 00:22:35.121
it was hard,
there were a lot of people,

00:22:35.121 --> 00:22:37.289
a long line,
so there was a waiting issue.

00:22:37.289 --> 00:22:42.144
But also people used to bribe
the priests, in order to get

00:22:42.144 --> 00:22:46.963
moved up on the front on line,
and they would also give great

00:22:46.963 --> 00:22:51.150
and beautiful gifts to the
temple people and to the temple,

00:22:51.150 --> 00:22:53.726
and to the priest.
In other words,

00:22:53.726 --> 00:22:57.589
people spent a lot of money to
consult the oracle.

00:22:57.589 --> 00:23:00.151
Now, ask yourself this,
especially if you're talking

00:23:00.151 --> 00:23:02.361
about Greeks,
are they going to keep shelling

00:23:02.361 --> 00:23:05.375
out money for an oracle that
gives them answers that turn out

00:23:05.375 --> 00:23:07.390
to be wrong?
No.

00:23:07.390 --> 00:23:12.046
Most of the things they
asked were questions that really

00:23:12.046 --> 00:23:15.986
had a yes or no answer,
and according to my thinking,

00:23:15.986 --> 00:23:19.579
there's no way they could have
been wrong very much.

00:23:19.579 --> 00:23:24.800
I think the oracle probably
gained its fame for being very

00:23:24.800 --> 00:23:28.829
good precisely at answering this
question.

00:23:28.829 --> 00:23:33.180
The question would have been
what will happen if I go and try

00:23:33.180 --> 00:23:36.661
to settle a colony at the place
which I will call

00:23:36.661 --> 00:23:41.084
Syracuse--that's what I've been
describing on the southeastern

00:23:41.084 --> 00:23:44.447
coast of Sicily.
The answer would come and the

00:23:44.447 --> 00:23:47.738
priests would give a response
that would be essentially

00:23:47.738 --> 00:23:49.821
straight.
It would either say something

00:23:49.821 --> 00:23:52.617
like--I'm not going to do the
words that they would have come

00:23:52.617 --> 00:23:55.112
up with,
but they would have said,

00:23:55.112 --> 00:23:58.840
yeah that's a good place to go
or don't do that,

00:23:58.840 --> 00:24:03.155
that's a terrible mistake.
Now, why would they be able to

00:24:03.155 --> 00:24:05.881
do that?
Because at some point in here,

00:24:05.881 --> 00:24:09.560
Delphi really did become the
navel of the universe;

00:24:09.560 --> 00:24:12.075
everybody came.
Now, you can bet when these

00:24:12.075 --> 00:24:14.027
folks came and consulted the
priest and said,

00:24:14.027 --> 00:24:15.980
could you please put us down on
the list,

00:24:15.980 --> 00:24:19.031
we want to consult the oracle,
the priest said sure have a

00:24:19.031 --> 00:24:21.120
beer, let's talk about your
hometown,

00:24:21.120 --> 00:24:24.496
what's going on out there.
What I'm suggesting to you is

00:24:24.496 --> 00:24:27.636
that this was the best
information gathering and

00:24:27.636 --> 00:24:31.509
storing device that existed in
the Mediterranean world.

00:24:31.509 --> 00:24:36.703
These people knew more than
anybody else about these things,

00:24:36.703 --> 00:24:42.250
and so consulting that oracle
was a very rational act indeed.

00:24:42.250 --> 00:24:45.035
Okay, now suppose you are the
oikistes,

00:24:45.035 --> 00:24:48.750
you've gotten the permission
from your city to go forward,

00:24:48.750 --> 00:24:52.327
and you go to the Delphic
Oracle and the Delphic Oracle

00:24:52.327 --> 00:24:56.269
says fine, by all means,
go where you want to go.

00:24:56.269 --> 00:25:01.033
Next thing, you got to go home
and you have to write up what

00:25:01.033 --> 00:25:05.069
amounts to a charter of
foundation for the city,

00:25:05.069 --> 00:25:09.065
which lays out how things are
going to work in this

00:25:09.065 --> 00:25:13.140
city--something about the
governmental structure,

00:25:13.140 --> 00:25:17.060
maybe even more fundamentally
how the land will be allotted,

00:25:17.060 --> 00:25:20.710
assigned, divided,
and so on so that when you go

00:25:20.710 --> 00:25:24.630
to recruit settlers,
everybody will know what he's

00:25:24.630 --> 00:25:29.990
getting and will decide whether
it's a good idea for him or not.

00:25:29.990 --> 00:25:35.478
Now, recruiting is
tremendously important because

00:25:35.478 --> 00:25:41.388
you need to have a certain
number of settlers to make the

00:25:41.388 --> 00:25:45.426
settlement viable.
You may not run into an

00:25:45.426 --> 00:25:49.980
enormously powerful collection
of natives, but you're going to

00:25:49.980 --> 00:25:53.631
get some kind of trouble.
It's foolish for you to assume

00:25:53.631 --> 00:25:56.130
you're not going to have any
problem out there.

00:25:56.130 --> 00:25:58.902
So you need a certain number of
people just for defense

00:25:58.902 --> 00:26:02.035
purposes, but beyond that you
need to have a certain number of

00:26:02.035 --> 00:26:04.705
people to carry out all the
functions that need to be

00:26:04.705 --> 00:26:07.170
carried out for a successful
polis.

00:26:07.170 --> 00:26:11.889
So however many that is,
that is what you try to recruit

00:26:11.889 --> 00:26:16.694
and you recruit typically at a
time when it's easy to get

00:26:16.694 --> 00:26:21.069
people together so you can tell
them the story.

00:26:21.069 --> 00:26:24.759
The best time would be at
some great festival.

00:26:24.759 --> 00:26:28.744
There are festivals held in
each city just for its own

00:26:28.744 --> 00:26:32.880
citizens and my guess is that
when you could do that,

00:26:32.880 --> 00:26:36.138
when you felt that you could
recruit a full colony from your

00:26:36.138 --> 00:26:40.289
fellow citizens in Corinth,
let us say, that's what you did.

00:26:40.289 --> 00:26:43.868
But it would often happen that
there were not enough

00:26:43.868 --> 00:26:48.289
Corinthians who were ready to go
with you on your expedition.

00:26:48.289 --> 00:26:52.386
So, you would try to take your
message to one of the

00:26:52.386 --> 00:26:56.885
Pan-Hellenic festivals which
were getting organized about

00:26:56.885 --> 00:26:58.813
this time.
As you know,

00:26:58.813 --> 00:27:02.430
the Olympic Games are alleged
to have started in 776.

00:27:02.430 --> 00:27:06.765
So, that would be a place where
Greeks from all over might come

00:27:06.765 --> 00:27:10.541
and you could then try to
recruit settlers for your new

00:27:10.541 --> 00:27:13.257
colony there,
and then we don't know

00:27:13.257 --> 00:27:17.630
precisely when but there were
Pan-Hellenic Games near Corinth,

00:27:17.630 --> 00:27:20.973
the Isthmian Games,
there were Pan-Hellenic Games

00:27:20.973 --> 00:27:24.943
at Delphi and there Pan-Hellenic
Games in the northeastern

00:27:24.943 --> 00:27:27.730
Peloponnesus at a town called
Nemea.

00:27:27.730 --> 00:27:32.457
So, there would always be some
opportunity for you to go out

00:27:32.457 --> 00:27:36.707
and make your pitch.
So now you have everything in

00:27:36.707 --> 00:27:41.425
place, you've recruited your
settlement, you get on your

00:27:41.425 --> 00:27:45.888
ships and sail,
in this case out to the west

00:27:45.888 --> 00:27:51.309
central Mediterranean,
you find your way to Sicily,

00:27:51.309 --> 00:27:57.664
work your way into the harbor
at Syracuse and things work out,

00:27:57.664 --> 00:28:03.289
and now we have this
apoikia called Syracuse.

00:28:03.289 --> 00:28:08.690
So, the next question I
think is, what is the

00:28:08.690 --> 00:28:15.440
relationship between Syracuse
which is the apoikia and

00:28:15.440 --> 00:28:19.705
Corinth,
which is the metropolis,

00:28:19.705 --> 00:28:22.831
the mother city;
that's what metropolis means by

00:28:22.831 --> 00:28:23.140
the way.

00:28:27.640 --> 00:28:31.716
First thing to brush from your
mind, along with the word colony

00:28:31.716 --> 00:28:34.150
as we have used it in modern
times,

00:28:34.150 --> 00:28:39.643
is the notion that the city of
Syracuse was sent out to be a

00:28:39.643 --> 00:28:45.606
colony, that Corinth controlled,
owned the city of Syracuse

00:28:45.606 --> 00:28:50.338
which it has sent out.
This is not the case--well,

00:28:50.338 --> 00:28:55.358
before the British gave Hong
Kong back, Hong Kong was a crown

00:28:55.358 --> 00:28:58.369
colony, it was British
territory.

00:28:58.369 --> 00:29:03.240
It was ruled by Britain and so
on.

00:29:03.240 --> 00:29:06.920
No, this is not what an
apoikia is.

00:29:06.920 --> 00:29:10.692
From the first,
Syracuse is an independent

00:29:10.692 --> 00:29:14.372
polis,
autonomous, self-governing,

00:29:14.372 --> 00:29:17.500
whatever regime it wants,
etc.

00:29:17.500 --> 00:29:24.650
It is not a subject of anybody,
not Corinth or anybody else.

00:29:24.650 --> 00:29:27.376
That's not the end of the story.
The question really is,

00:29:27.376 --> 00:29:30.517
so now we know that,
what kind of relations did they

00:29:30.517 --> 00:29:33.591
have?
I would say there are three

00:29:33.591 --> 00:29:38.769
categories that they fall into.
The most typical,

00:29:38.769 --> 00:29:44.725
the usual, everything else is
an exception is that there are

00:29:44.725 --> 00:29:49.671
friendly relations between the
mother city and the

00:29:49.671 --> 00:29:54.677
apoikia,
but keep in mind that they are

00:29:54.677 --> 00:29:58.958
always independent,
and an example is in the

00:29:58.958 --> 00:30:04.418
Peloponnesian War.
Syracuse finds itself besieged

00:30:04.418 --> 00:30:09.886
by the Athenians.
They go to Corinth asking the

00:30:09.886 --> 00:30:16.640
Corinthians to please help us.
The Corinthians are free;

00:30:16.640 --> 00:30:21.580
they will be violating no law
or sacred bond if they say,

00:30:21.580 --> 00:30:25.549
sorry we really don't feel like
doing that.

00:30:25.549 --> 00:30:29.286
It would be thought they were
not behaving very well,

00:30:29.286 --> 00:30:33.311
but they would have been as I
say, perfectly within every

00:30:33.311 --> 00:30:35.970
right you can imagine to do
that.

00:30:35.970 --> 00:30:40.118
But the typical reaction would
be that the Corinthians would

00:30:40.118 --> 00:30:42.579
help, to the extent first of
all,

00:30:42.579 --> 00:30:46.752
that they could and secondly,
to the extent that it was

00:30:46.752 --> 00:30:50.446
consistent with their interests.
Well, in fact,

00:30:50.446 --> 00:30:54.635
the Corinthians send very
little, send a couple of ships

00:30:54.635 --> 00:30:57.141
and a general,
which turn out to be

00:30:57.141 --> 00:31:00.229
tremendously important,
but they couldn't have known

00:31:00.229 --> 00:31:03.023
that in advance.
From where we sit,

00:31:03.023 --> 00:31:06.983
it looks like the Corinthians
were making a gesture of

00:31:06.983 --> 00:31:09.084
friendship,
of solidarity,

00:31:09.084 --> 00:31:13.154
the kind of thing you would
expect a mother city to do,

00:31:13.154 --> 00:31:16.620
not to ignore its
apoikia when it was in

00:31:16.620 --> 00:31:21.109
trouble.
So that's all that they did.

00:31:21.109 --> 00:31:23.622
First of all,
it was normal for the

00:31:23.622 --> 00:31:27.539
apoikia to turn to the
mother city for help,

00:31:27.539 --> 00:31:31.306
and it was normal for the
mother city to be inclined to

00:31:31.306 --> 00:31:34.299
help if they could do it.
That's normal.

00:31:34.299 --> 00:31:36.423
I think if you can imagine of
the many, many,

00:31:36.423 --> 00:31:39.077
many colonies there were,
that would have been the usual

00:31:39.077 --> 00:31:41.768
arrangement.
Now, there are exceptions in

00:31:41.768 --> 00:31:44.852
both directions,
and as it happens the cases I

00:31:44.852 --> 00:31:48.210
know best have to do with the
city of Corinth.

00:31:48.210 --> 00:31:52.155
Corinth sent out a lot of
colonies, which is why we know

00:31:52.155 --> 00:31:54.809
something about their
arrangements.

00:31:54.809 --> 00:31:57.649
The ones I'm talking about all
have to do with the

00:31:57.649 --> 00:32:01.009
Peloponnesian War which is one
of the reasons why we know a

00:32:01.009 --> 00:32:05.142
little bit about it,
because Thucydides tells us the

00:32:05.142 --> 00:32:07.966
details of it.
Well, we know,

00:32:07.966 --> 00:32:13.312
thanks to Thucydides,
that it had become normal for

00:32:13.312 --> 00:32:18.230
Corinth to send out to its
colony Potidaea,

00:32:18.230 --> 00:32:23.140
located on the Chalcidic
peninsula, those three fingers

00:32:23.140 --> 00:32:28.960
sticking down into the Aegean
Sea from the mainland of Greece,

00:32:28.960 --> 00:32:32.769
this is a town on one of those
fingers.

00:32:32.769 --> 00:32:37.079
Potidaea every year
received magistrates who

00:32:37.079 --> 00:32:42.579
governed their city from Corinth
and this was not imposed,

00:32:42.579 --> 00:32:47.480
this was not by force,
this was by mutual agreement.

00:32:47.480 --> 00:32:51.110
So, Corinth really had a very
great deal to say about what was

00:32:51.110 --> 00:32:54.237
going on in Potidaea.
So, when Potidaea got into

00:32:54.237 --> 00:32:57.347
trouble with Athens,
and found itself besieged,

00:32:57.347 --> 00:33:00.930
Corinth sent a real army to go
in there and fight,

00:33:00.930 --> 00:33:04.871
and I think that's because of
this very special relationship

00:33:04.871 --> 00:33:07.773
that they had.
At the other end of the

00:33:07.773 --> 00:33:12.477
spectrum it's again Corinth and
they have a colony up in the

00:33:12.477 --> 00:33:17.987
northwest called Corcyra,
it is the modern Island of

00:33:17.987 --> 00:33:25.297
Corfu, and this colony was
clearly established earlier than

00:33:25.297 --> 00:33:27.441
664,
because that's the first time

00:33:27.441 --> 00:33:28.920
we hear of its taking any
action;

00:33:28.920 --> 00:33:33.480
it's been around for a while,
very early colony.

00:33:33.480 --> 00:33:37.978
From the earliest times,
Corcyra does not get along with

00:33:37.978 --> 00:33:42.915
the mother city of Corinth.
The first relationship between

00:33:42.915 --> 00:33:47.448
them is a navel battle,
and thereafter we hear of them

00:33:47.448 --> 00:33:52.495
quarrelling and fighting with
each other just about at least

00:33:52.495 --> 00:33:56.514
once a century right on down
until we get to the

00:33:56.514 --> 00:34:01.988
Peloponnesian War when a quarrel
over who's what out in that area

00:34:01.988 --> 00:34:06.440
between Corinth and Corcyra is,
I would say,

00:34:06.440 --> 00:34:11.678
the first instigating element
in bringing on the Peloponnesian

00:34:11.678 --> 00:34:14.329
War.
Okay, so this gives you

00:34:14.329 --> 00:34:18.505
some idea of the range of
possible relationships between

00:34:18.505 --> 00:34:22.470
colony and mother city.
I just want to emphasize one

00:34:22.470 --> 00:34:26.807
more time, that the overwhelming
normal situation is the first

00:34:26.807 --> 00:34:29.580
one I described,
friendly relations.

00:34:29.580 --> 00:34:32.631
Why not?
These guys that have gone out,

00:34:32.631 --> 00:34:35.730
let us say to Syracuse,
they are your people,

00:34:35.730 --> 00:34:39.933
they have relatives back home,
they have friends back home,

00:34:39.933 --> 00:34:44.628
it is natural--oh by the way,
they're accustomed to worship

00:34:44.628 --> 00:34:48.849
the gods in the same way that
the Corinthians do.

00:34:48.849 --> 00:34:51.878
We do know, again,
Thucydides is our source,

00:34:51.878 --> 00:34:55.892
that it was customary for
colonies to send representatives

00:34:55.892 --> 00:35:00.329
back to the mother city for the
religious observations that were

00:35:00.329 --> 00:35:03.861
common to them all,
so that those create good

00:35:03.861 --> 00:35:06.680
feelings.
They feel like their relatives,

00:35:06.680 --> 00:35:11.381
and what could be more natural.
You're out there in Sicily and

00:35:11.381 --> 00:35:14.996
you discover,
of course, that you don't have

00:35:14.996 --> 00:35:20.039
all of the things that you used
to have available to you,

00:35:20.039 --> 00:35:23.099
that used to be made let us say
in Corinth.

00:35:23.099 --> 00:35:25.637
As a matter of fact,
in the early days,

00:35:25.637 --> 00:35:29.375
Corinth was a great center of
painted pottery and was the

00:35:29.375 --> 00:35:32.179
leading producer and exporter of
that.

00:35:32.179 --> 00:35:35.393
So, maybe you wanted a really
fine pot of the kind you used to

00:35:35.393 --> 00:35:38.659
be able to walk to the corner
and pick up at a pottery shop,

00:35:38.659 --> 00:35:41.871
but you can't get now,
so you would want to buy what

00:35:41.871 --> 00:35:44.510
the Corinthians sell.
Guess what?

00:35:44.510 --> 00:35:48.380
You've got great grain fields
out there in Syracuse.

00:35:48.380 --> 00:35:51.635
Hard to believe today,
but Sicily was one of the major

00:35:51.635 --> 00:35:54.829
granaries of the Mediterranean
world at that time,

00:35:54.829 --> 00:35:58.236
tremendously fruitful,
able to grow the best possible

00:35:58.236 --> 00:36:00.530
crops, very good wheat and so
on.

00:36:00.530 --> 00:36:04.627
Corinth always needs that kind
of stuff, so we sell you our

00:36:04.627 --> 00:36:08.689
wheat, you sell us your pottery,
you sell good wine that we

00:36:08.689 --> 00:36:12.328
can't grow yet and maybe never
will be able to grow in our

00:36:12.328 --> 00:36:14.670
neighborhood,
so on and so forth.

00:36:14.670 --> 00:36:19.407
So you can see why it would be
very natural for all sorts of

00:36:19.407 --> 00:36:23.020
ties to unite these colony and
mother city.

00:36:26.599 --> 00:36:30.638
Maybe I ought to just give you
a chance before I turn to the

00:36:30.638 --> 00:36:34.197
next question to ask any
questions that still are not

00:36:34.197 --> 00:36:38.030
clear for you about this
phenomenon of colonization.

