00:48:51.250 --> 00:48:55.223
of Sicily and the Greeks will
have to fight the Carthaginians

00:48:55.223 --> 00:48:58.800
over the years for control of
the island of Sicily.

00:48:58.800 --> 00:49:03.541
So, that's how far east they
get and in time the

00:49:03.541 --> 00:49:09.695
Carthaginians also cross over
into Spain and they control some

00:49:09.695 --> 00:49:14.840
portion of the Spanish coast
closest to Africa.

00:49:14.840 --> 00:49:18.544
So, there are no Greeks there.
They're shut out for the same

00:49:18.544 --> 00:49:21.100
reasons.
However, once you get beyond

00:49:21.100 --> 00:49:24.962
the Carthaginians advance into
Spain, there are now Greek

00:49:24.962 --> 00:49:28.962
cities on the coast of Spain and
there continue to be Greek

00:49:28.962 --> 00:49:31.183
cities,
not everywhere,

00:49:31.183 --> 00:49:36.945
but in a spotty way into France
of which the most important and

00:49:36.945 --> 00:49:41.870
famous is the one that the
Romans called Masillia,

00:49:41.870 --> 00:49:48.570
Marseille, a Greek town.
So is Nice a Greek town.

00:49:48.570 --> 00:49:52.507
Nice was Nikea,
victory town and there are

00:49:52.507 --> 00:49:56.233
several others.
So, they know where to go,

00:49:56.233 --> 00:49:58.730
the Riviera,
places like that.

00:49:58.730 --> 00:50:00.440
Now, what about the Italian
Riviera?

00:50:00.440 --> 00:50:03.189
That's pretty nifty.
Were the Greek colonies near

00:50:03.189 --> 00:50:04.950
Portofino where you could put
in?

00:50:04.950 --> 00:50:07.912
No.
And the reason was in the

00:50:07.912 --> 00:50:11.030
northern part of Italy,
there were Etruscans,

00:50:11.030 --> 00:50:15.354
another powerful ancient people
who control their own area and

00:50:15.354 --> 00:50:19.820
were not about to have anybody
colonizing their territory.

00:50:19.820 --> 00:50:26.066
However, when you keep going
south in Italy,

00:50:26.066 --> 00:50:34.927
past Rome, Roman tradition says
the city was founded in 754 or

00:50:34.927 --> 00:50:37.490
753?
753.

00:50:37.490 --> 00:50:41.079
So, everybody agrees about that.
Certainly not before that.

00:50:41.079 --> 00:50:44.003
So, in the period we're talking
about there are no Romans that

00:50:44.003 --> 00:50:48.147
you have to worry about.
So, south of Rome there is a

00:50:48.147 --> 00:50:52.389
tremendous colonizing of
southern Italy.

00:50:52.389 --> 00:50:55.380
Greek cities are all over the
place.

00:50:55.380 --> 00:51:00.251
So Greek was that area that
when the Romans do come to

00:51:00.251 --> 00:51:05.950
dominate most of Italy and sort
of move up against the southern

00:51:05.950 --> 00:51:10.913
region they refer to the whole
southern portion of that

00:51:10.913 --> 00:51:14.590
peninsula as Magna
Graecia,

00:51:14.590 --> 00:51:18.860
great Greece because they're
all Greeks down there.

00:51:18.860 --> 00:51:24.499
Then finally,
down we go to Sicily and there

00:51:24.499 --> 00:51:30.110
you have the east coast.
I would say two-thirds of the

00:51:30.110 --> 00:51:34.510
coast of the island of Sicily is
filled with Greek towns.

00:51:34.510 --> 00:51:38.510
The third to the west is under
Carthaginian control.

00:51:38.510 --> 00:51:42.309
The inland, the Greeks don't
move in there.

00:51:42.309 --> 00:51:45.430
The natives Sicilians inhabit
that territory and the Greeks

00:51:45.430 --> 00:51:49.110
are not interested.
You will find very rare of the

00:51:49.110 --> 00:51:53.445
case of a Greek city,
which is founded away from the

00:51:53.445 --> 00:51:56.319
sea;
they always wanted to be close

00:51:56.319 --> 00:51:59.130
to the sea for varieties of
reasons.

00:51:59.130 --> 00:52:03.420
So, now I hope you have in
your mind a picture of the way

00:52:03.420 --> 00:52:07.139
the Greek world had expanded by
the time this wave of

00:52:07.139 --> 00:52:10.500
colonization was
complete--pretty complete,

00:52:10.500 --> 00:52:14.780
sometime in the seventh century
B.C.

00:52:14.780 --> 00:52:18.464
Just a word about the leading
colonizers, because I think

00:52:18.464 --> 00:52:21.360
there's something to be learned
from that.

00:52:21.360 --> 00:52:23.909
One of the things you kind of
speculate about,

00:52:23.909 --> 00:52:26.460
and wonder about,
why did some cities send out

00:52:26.460 --> 00:52:29.671
lots of colonies,
some cities send out only a

00:52:29.671 --> 00:52:33.190
few, and others none at all for
quite a while.

00:52:33.190 --> 00:52:36.579
Well, if you see who does then
you may have a clue.

00:52:36.579 --> 00:52:41.800
Well, here is a list of the
early extensive colonizers.

00:52:41.800 --> 00:52:45.860
Miletus, I mentioned to you
from Asia Minor;

00:52:45.860 --> 00:52:51.052
Corinth on the isthmus;
Megara right next door to

00:52:51.052 --> 00:52:55.889
Corinth, also more or less on
the isthmus.

00:52:55.889 --> 00:53:01.196
Then we turn to the island of
Euboea, that long island that's

00:53:01.196 --> 00:53:05.530
right next to the east coast of
Attica, Euboea.

00:53:05.530 --> 00:53:08.853
There were two important cities
in the northern part of that

00:53:08.853 --> 00:53:11.508
island.
One was Calkis and the other

00:53:11.508 --> 00:53:15.881
one was Eretria and we hear
about them relatively early in

00:53:15.881 --> 00:53:19.500
the eighth century,
already being very important,

00:53:19.500 --> 00:53:23.494
very strong and fighting each
other in a famous war that they

00:53:23.494 --> 00:53:26.077
fought.
But these cities were very

00:53:26.077 --> 00:53:29.690
active in colonizing in a
variety of directions.

00:53:29.690 --> 00:53:34.139
Lots of these towns sent
colonists up north into the

00:53:34.139 --> 00:53:39.724
Dardanelles and so on and beyond
and some of the same cities send

00:53:39.724 --> 00:53:44.143
out colonies to Sicily,
so that for the real colonizing

00:53:44.143 --> 00:53:48.136
states there was no limit to
where they would send people who

00:53:48.136 --> 00:53:52.558
wanted to go in those areas.
It is also interesting to

00:53:52.558 --> 00:53:57.681
notice who does not colonize at
this early period and the answer

00:53:57.681 --> 00:54:03.130
is all the most famous cities of
Greece in the Classical Period.

00:54:03.130 --> 00:54:06.932
Athens doesn't send out a
colony until sometime in the

00:54:06.932 --> 00:54:10.468
sixth century.
Sparta starts at an early

00:54:10.468 --> 00:54:16.010
point, sends out a colony to
southern Italy at some time,

00:54:16.010 --> 00:54:19.288
probably early,
they sent out a colony to an

00:54:19.288 --> 00:54:21.880
island in the Aegean Sea,
Melos,

00:54:21.880 --> 00:54:27.550
and then they stopped and never
sent out another colony.

00:54:27.550 --> 00:54:32.133
Finally, Thebes,
the greatest city in Boeotia,

00:54:32.133 --> 00:54:37.424
also does not colonize.
So what can we speculate is the

00:54:37.424 --> 00:54:41.249
meaning of that?
What we find is that the states

00:54:41.249 --> 00:54:45.215
who are doing most of the
colonizing are located where

00:54:45.215 --> 00:54:49.630
most of the trade was going on
at this point in history,

00:54:49.630 --> 00:54:51.909
and also most of the
manufacturing.

00:54:51.909 --> 00:54:55.780
When I say manufacturing,
you understand everything is

00:54:55.780 --> 00:54:58.847
done by hand,
but you see things like shops

00:54:58.847 --> 00:55:03.010
that contain a number of slaves
working for a master.

00:55:03.010 --> 00:55:05.933
In some cases,
especially the later on you go,

00:55:05.933 --> 00:55:09.376
some shops that have quite a
few slaves that worked to

00:55:09.376 --> 00:55:12.891
produce these things.
It's the handy craft industry

00:55:12.891 --> 00:55:15.110
but it's an industry
nonetheless.

00:55:15.110 --> 00:55:21.116
Well, these places are the ones
that have the trade,

00:55:21.116 --> 00:55:24.767
the industry,
and also engage in

00:55:24.767 --> 00:55:28.807
colonization.
Moreover, as we will see,

00:55:28.807 --> 00:55:33.208
there will be internal trouble
in the form of political

00:55:33.208 --> 00:55:36.158
quarreling,
economic conflict,

00:55:36.158 --> 00:55:40.880
and finally warfare,
civil wars occur in some of

00:55:40.880 --> 00:55:45.000
these cities leading to the
emergence,

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:49.435
and in the next topic I'll turn
to, of the establishment of

00:55:49.435 --> 00:55:53.259
tyrannies, as the way of
resolving for a time these

00:55:53.259 --> 00:55:57.159
terribly tumultuous conditions
in those cities.

00:55:57.159 --> 00:56:01.718
All of these things are
true of places like Corinth,

00:56:01.718 --> 00:56:05.199
Megara and possibly Chalcis and
Eretria.

00:56:05.199 --> 00:56:10.723
So, it is easy to see that
where there is that kind of

00:56:10.723 --> 00:56:16.142
conflict and trouble,
there would be people who would

00:56:16.142 --> 00:56:20.519
want to flee that and to go
elsewhere.

00:56:20.519 --> 00:56:24.076
It might well be that the
people who won those wars,

00:56:24.076 --> 00:56:27.005
internal wars,
would have been glad to send

00:56:27.005 --> 00:56:31.050
them away rather than to have
these discontented people and

00:56:31.050 --> 00:56:35.025
these folks who were their
enemies hanging around town and

00:56:35.025 --> 00:56:38.922
making trouble.
It is only speculation,

00:56:38.922 --> 00:56:44.804
but it seems to make sense and
we know we don't hear of such

00:56:44.804 --> 00:56:49.690
troubles within Athens and
Thebes, and Sparta.

00:56:49.690 --> 00:56:54.276
It also is possible,
again it's just speculation,

00:56:54.276 --> 00:56:59.914
that population pressure might
well be greater in the cities

00:56:59.914 --> 00:57:03.598
that did the colonizing.
They tended,

00:57:03.598 --> 00:57:08.640
in general, not to have as much
farmland as the places that I

00:57:08.640 --> 00:57:12.170
have described as not being
colonizers,

00:57:12.170 --> 00:57:16.022
who may not have felt the
pressures of land hunger,

00:57:16.022 --> 00:57:20.030
which was so important in
motivating colonization.

00:57:20.030 --> 00:57:27.095
So, that may explain why some
of the states did and others did

00:57:27.095 --> 00:57:28.834
not.
Finally,

00:57:28.834 --> 00:57:33.708
what are the consequences to
the Greek experience of this

00:57:33.708 --> 00:57:37.800
phenomenon of this outburst of
colonization?

00:57:37.800 --> 00:57:42.548
Several things come to mind.
First of all,

00:57:42.548 --> 00:57:47.850
the Greeks now live in places
where they never lived before

00:57:47.850 --> 00:57:53.335
and their presence has a real
impact of a different degree in

00:57:53.335 --> 00:57:57.400
every place.
I would say that typically

00:57:57.400 --> 00:58:03.289
their impact was greater in the
west and the north than it was

00:58:03.289 --> 00:58:08.047
in the east and the south.
The reason for that was that in

00:58:08.047 --> 00:58:11.268
the east and in south,
the Greeks lived among people

00:58:11.268 --> 00:58:15.119
who were more civilized than
they, who were more advanced.

00:58:15.119 --> 00:58:19.432
They had very little to teach
or to impose upon those people

00:58:19.432 --> 00:58:23.060
rather than vice versa.
I think that I would imagine

00:58:23.060 --> 00:58:26.661
the Greeks sopping up all sorts
of useful and interesting

00:58:26.661 --> 00:58:30.583
information from their neighbors
in the east and the south and

00:58:30.583 --> 00:58:34.023
there's no question about it.
If you look at Greece in this

00:58:34.023 --> 00:58:36.269
period, I don't know if I've
used this term before,

00:58:36.269 --> 00:58:40.580
but some scholars refer to this
general period we're talking

00:58:40.580 --> 00:58:45.109
about as the Greek renaissance
by analogy to the renaissance in

00:58:45.109 --> 00:58:47.528
Italy.
There's something to it,

00:58:47.528 --> 00:58:51.326
because things happened in this
period that are revolutionary in

00:58:51.326 --> 00:58:54.524
the arts,
in the thinking of people,

00:58:54.524 --> 00:58:59.855
philosophy is going to be
invented in Miletus probably in

00:58:59.855 --> 00:59:05.119
this sixth century B.C.
Well, Miletus was on the main

00:59:05.119 --> 00:59:10.602
routes to all of the places
where advanced knowledge could

00:59:10.602 --> 00:59:13.679
be found, Mesopotamia,
Egypt.

00:59:13.679 --> 00:59:19.249
Anybody who looks at Greek
mythology and Greek poetry,

00:59:19.249 --> 00:59:25.870
and Greek stories sees there is
a powerful influence coming into

00:59:25.870 --> 00:59:31.860
Greek thought from mainly the
Mesopotamian direction.

00:59:31.860 --> 00:59:35.812
Anybody who looks at the
earliest Greek art for quite

00:59:35.812 --> 00:59:40.449
some time, I'm talking about
sculpture and temple building,

00:59:40.449 --> 00:59:46.489
will see the influence of Egypt
enormously powerfully.

00:59:46.489 --> 00:59:52.899
So, the Greeks are sopping up
tremendously useful information

00:59:52.899 --> 00:59:57.657
and talent, and skills,
and all sorts of things that

00:59:57.657 --> 01:00:00.639
help explain what's going to be
coming.

01:00:00.639 --> 01:00:04.420
It is inconceivable the
Greeks could have developed a

01:00:04.420 --> 01:00:07.931
civilization that they did
without contact with these

01:00:07.931 --> 01:00:12.050
eastern civilizations and
learned a great deal from them.

01:00:12.050 --> 01:00:16.131
Now, people--some people make
an enormous jump from that and

01:00:16.131 --> 01:00:20.489
wrongly suggest that what the
Greeks basically did was--well,

01:00:20.489 --> 01:00:23.916
if you want to take the most
extreme statement of it,

01:00:23.916 --> 01:00:27.079
stole their civilization from
the other folks.

01:00:27.079 --> 01:00:30.002
Well, if you take a look at the
Greek civilization let us say in

01:00:30.002 --> 01:00:32.587
the classical period,
those other cultures wouldn't

01:00:32.587 --> 01:00:35.885
have had a clue what the Greeks
were doing, so different was the

01:00:35.885 --> 01:00:39.856
Greek experience from theirs.
But what is undeniably true is

01:00:39.856 --> 01:00:44.449
that the Greeks learned very
important and valuable things,

01:00:44.449 --> 01:00:48.904
and adapted what they learned
through their own way of life

01:00:48.904 --> 01:00:52.130
and produced something really
quite new,

01:00:52.130 --> 01:00:57.290
and in many fundamental ways,
not only new but the opposite

01:00:57.290 --> 01:01:01.650
of the places from which these
things had come.

01:01:01.650 --> 01:01:05.264
There was also,
of course, some influence of

01:01:05.264 --> 01:01:08.340
the Greeks on the people they
went to.

01:01:08.340 --> 01:01:11.635
Obviously, I started out by
saying this would probably have

01:01:11.635 --> 01:01:14.760
been felt most strongly in the
west and in the north,

01:01:14.760 --> 01:01:17.134
where the people,
who lived there,

01:01:17.134 --> 01:01:20.948
before the Greeks came,
were not civilized or were not

01:01:20.948 --> 01:01:24.030
highly civilized.
They did not have great urban

01:01:24.030 --> 01:01:27.172
cultures and civilizations,
long traditions of learning and

01:01:27.172 --> 01:01:29.350
so on.
No, they weren't like that,

01:01:29.350 --> 01:01:32.795
the Greeks were ahead of them
and it's evident that they

01:01:32.795 --> 01:01:36.489
borrowed stuff from the Greeks
in every element of life,

01:01:36.489 --> 01:01:39.733
although it didn't shape their
lives in a potent,

01:01:39.733 --> 01:01:43.878
fundamental way.
But that's the way influence

01:01:43.878 --> 01:01:48.231
ran in that part of the world.
Of course,

01:01:48.231 --> 01:01:53.075
another tremendously important
consequence of colonization was

01:01:53.075 --> 01:01:56.913
the growth of commerce,
of trade for the reasons I've

01:01:56.913 --> 01:01:59.788
already given you,
but beyond that the Greeks of

01:01:59.788 --> 01:02:02.268
course,
now had access to food stuffs

01:02:02.268 --> 01:02:04.974
and other things out in where
they settled,

01:02:04.974 --> 01:02:08.840
which gave them a basis for
trading with the mother city,

01:02:08.840 --> 01:02:11.116
which meant there were markets
for the mother city,

01:02:11.116 --> 01:02:12.710
which they hadn't existed
before.

01:02:12.710 --> 01:02:16.869
But also, the Greeks were in
touch with people beyond where

01:02:16.869 --> 01:02:19.522
they settled,
so they could obtain raw

01:02:19.522 --> 01:02:22.750
materials that were not
available before,

01:02:22.750 --> 01:02:27.334
and also manufactured things
that they might not have had

01:02:27.334 --> 01:02:30.725
access to before.
All of which they would have

01:02:30.725 --> 01:02:34.528
used some for themselves and
then engaged in trade with the

01:02:34.528 --> 01:02:36.662
old Greek cities.
In other words,

01:02:36.662 --> 01:02:39.625
you don't need a very great
imagination to see how this

01:02:39.625 --> 01:02:41.820
would be a terrific boom to
commerce.

01:02:41.820 --> 01:02:45.803
Think about it for a second,
what will this be and how will

01:02:45.803 --> 01:02:50.130
this effect what's happening in
the cities, the polis?

01:02:50.130 --> 01:02:53.000
More and more people,
and again I want to remind you,

01:02:53.000 --> 01:02:55.050
never anything approaching a
majority,

01:02:55.050 --> 01:02:58.984
but more and more people would
be making their living in a way

01:02:58.984 --> 01:03:02.702
that was not agricultural.
They would be in commerce and

01:03:02.702 --> 01:03:06.526
they would be in industry in
this small sense and doing all

01:03:06.526 --> 01:03:10.350
the various things that are not
farming and so you now have

01:03:10.350 --> 01:03:14.438
classes or groups of people who
have interests rather different

01:03:14.438 --> 01:03:19.120
from those of the most primitive
polis you could imagine.

01:03:22.559 --> 01:03:26.666
Some scholars early on in the
century, moved by Marxist

01:03:26.666 --> 01:03:31.610
theories, suggested that you had
a capitalist class growing up,

01:03:31.610 --> 01:03:33.390
there's just no evidence of
that;

01:03:33.390 --> 01:03:37.055
it's just wrong.
My guess is that the earliest

01:03:37.055 --> 01:03:42.338
traders of any scope were
probably noblemen who also had

01:03:42.338 --> 01:03:46.534
land and estates back home,
but who had the opportunity,

01:03:46.534 --> 01:03:48.366
the know-how,
the connections to make it

01:03:48.366 --> 01:03:50.480
possible to make a lot of living
in trade.

01:03:50.480 --> 01:03:54.795
Even so, while you don't have a
class of separate people who are

01:03:54.795 --> 01:03:58.699
just in the business of making
things and making money,

01:03:58.699 --> 01:04:02.319
you do have people who are
engaged in those activities and

01:04:02.319 --> 01:04:06.383
who have some interests that are
different from those of the rest

01:04:06.383 --> 01:04:09.050
of their people who are only
hoplites.

01:04:09.050 --> 01:04:11.532
It is, I think,
part of a conglomerate of

01:04:11.532 --> 01:04:14.974
activities you want to keep in
your mind that is going on here

01:04:14.974 --> 01:04:17.739
and this is what I'm really
trying to get at,

01:04:17.739 --> 01:04:20.099
socially and economically,
and politically.

01:04:20.099 --> 01:04:22.796
You have to imagine,
on the one hand,

01:04:22.796 --> 01:04:26.465
the hoplite revolution,
which I do not shrink from

01:04:26.465 --> 01:04:29.311
saying, but it's a very
debatable term,

01:04:29.311 --> 01:04:32.527
is going on.
More and more farmers are

01:04:32.527 --> 01:04:35.290
becoming independent,
self-sustaining,

01:04:35.290 --> 01:04:39.099
hoplite farmers of the kind
that I've described.

01:04:39.099 --> 01:04:42.918
You can't expect them to
continue to live in the same way

01:04:42.918 --> 01:04:46.555
as they did before,
deferential to their betters,

01:04:46.555 --> 01:04:49.978
that is to say,
tugging their forelocks before

01:04:49.978 --> 01:04:54.237
the aristocrats and just leaving
all the decisions to the

01:04:54.237 --> 01:04:57.355
aristocrats.
They're not going to feel the

01:04:57.355 --> 01:05:00.251
same way about it,
there's going to be pressure

01:05:00.251 --> 01:05:03.525
from them for a better
participation in the decisions

01:05:03.525 --> 01:05:07.854
that are made in the state.
And also there will be some

01:05:07.854 --> 01:05:12.825
rich people, very rich people,
rich in a different way from

01:05:12.825 --> 01:05:18.110
the way people used to be rich;
rich meant the best land.

01:05:18.110 --> 01:05:23.851
Now, there will be people who
will have wealth in the form of

01:05:23.851 --> 01:05:28.539
precious things and I would use
the word money.

01:05:28.539 --> 01:05:31.470
I'm not going to use the word
coinage because that's very

01:05:31.470 --> 01:05:34.347
debated, and anyway there
certainly weren't any coins in

01:05:34.347 --> 01:05:37.905
Greece as early as say 750.
But that doesn't mean there was

01:05:37.905 --> 01:05:41.344
no money.
You could have weighed out

01:05:41.344 --> 01:05:44.909
precious metal,
which would be money.

01:05:44.909 --> 01:05:49.670
Shekels, as in the Bible,
are originally not coins;

01:05:49.670 --> 01:05:53.463
they are quantities,
weights of something and come

01:05:53.463 --> 01:05:56.250
to mean weights of silver or
gold.

01:05:56.250 --> 01:06:01.630
So now you have a change in
fundamental economic things.

01:06:01.630 --> 01:06:05.875
Well, all of this is tied up
with this colonial story I've

01:06:05.875 --> 01:06:09.194
been telling you.
Finally, I think,

01:06:09.194 --> 01:06:15.803
it works in both directions at
the same time in terms of the

01:06:15.803 --> 01:06:22.860
impact all of these changes have
on the political situation.

01:06:22.860 --> 01:06:27.817
On the one hand the changes,
that is (A) the rise of the

01:06:27.817 --> 01:06:32.092
hoplite class;
(B) the development of lots of

01:06:32.092 --> 01:06:37.757
commerce and industry and wealth
in a new kind and people who

01:06:37.757 --> 01:06:42.099
don't fit into the old
traditional society;

01:06:42.099 --> 01:06:46.164
new way has to be found to fit
them in because,

01:06:46.164 --> 01:06:51.059
as I say, they don't fit.
That creates trouble.

01:06:51.059 --> 01:06:54.944
As we shall see very shortly,
that trouble often takes the

01:06:54.944 --> 01:06:58.079
form of first of factional
struggles within the

01:06:58.079 --> 01:07:01.276
aristocracy,
which then after awhile come to

01:07:01.276 --> 01:07:05.013
involve people outside the
aristocracy, which ultimately

01:07:05.013 --> 01:07:08.750
come to civil war in which
certainly the people who have

01:07:08.750 --> 01:07:11.739
become the most important
fighting men,

01:07:11.739 --> 01:07:14.760
the hoplites,
become engaged on one side or

01:07:14.760 --> 01:07:17.710
the other or perhaps sometimes
on both.

01:07:17.710 --> 01:07:20.406
So that's the,
what you might say,

01:07:20.406 --> 01:07:23.030
is the negative side of the
story.

01:07:23.030 --> 01:07:26.557
But colonization,
especially, some scholars have

01:07:26.557 --> 01:07:29.260
pointed out, I think
persuasively,

01:07:29.260 --> 01:07:35.367
also for some considerable time
provided an answer to that

01:07:35.367 --> 01:07:39.760
problem in the form of an escape
valve,

01:07:39.760 --> 01:07:43.358
where you had these people who
were losers and angry and

01:07:43.358 --> 01:07:47.414
troubled, or people who had in
any case were not happy with the

01:07:47.414 --> 01:07:50.489
way things were going in their
mother city.

01:07:50.489 --> 01:07:52.510
Well, they didn't have to stay
and fight it out.

01:07:52.510 --> 01:07:57.398
They could go away and they
did, in very considerable

01:07:57.398 --> 01:08:02.380
numbers, and so one is easily
reminded of the American

01:08:02.380 --> 01:08:05.562
experience,
as it has often been

01:08:05.562 --> 01:08:09.905
interpreted, in which the
frontier is seen to be a

01:08:09.905 --> 01:08:14.780
tremendously valuable safety
valve to the Americans,

01:08:14.780 --> 01:08:17.970
first as colonists,
and then as independent people.

01:08:17.970 --> 01:08:22.219
Americans didn't have the
kind of terrible class warfare

01:08:22.219 --> 01:08:26.540
and the terrible warfare within
cities that the Europeans had

01:08:26.540 --> 01:08:30.069
experienced throughout most of
their history,

01:08:30.069 --> 01:08:34.824
because really unhappy and
angry people could always go

01:08:34.824 --> 01:08:38.932
west, get new places.
I mean, fundamentally,

01:08:38.932 --> 01:08:44.897
Kansas is a colony in a certain
Greek sense, all of these places

01:08:44.897 --> 01:08:48.109
are.
So, that's part of the story of

01:08:48.109 --> 01:08:52.880
why America had the very lucky
early history that it had.

01:08:52.880 --> 01:08:57.516
So, I think we have to
understand that colonization

01:08:57.516 --> 01:09:03.079
provided something analogous to
that for the Greek people.

01:09:03.079 --> 01:09:06.933
So now, here we are somewhere
in the seventh century,

01:09:06.933 --> 01:09:11.750
most of these places I've been
talking about have been settled,

01:09:11.750 --> 01:09:16.179
the currents that I have been
describing are flowing and the

01:09:16.179 --> 01:09:20.684
kinds of problems they have give
rise to what will be felt in

01:09:20.684 --> 01:09:25.113
most of the towns and that is
the proper introduction to the

01:09:25.113 --> 01:09:28.239
next topic,
which I'll discuss next year.

01:09:28.239 --> 01:09:32.000
No not--it seems like a year,
but it's next Tuesday actually.

